<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1187,1790]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1187,1213]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Fartyal, R. S. &amp; Gao, J. J. &amp; Toda, M. J. &amp; Hu, Y. G. &amp; Takano, K. T. &amp; Suwito, A. &amp; Katoh, T. &amp; Takigahira, T. &amp; Yin, J. T." box="[454,665,1188,1214]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="763 - 782" refId="ref32284" refString="Fartyal, R. S., Gao, J. J., Toda, M. J., Hu, Y. G., Takano, K. T., Suwito, A., Katoh, T., Takigahira, T. &amp; Yin, J. T. (2013) Colocasiomyia (Diptera: Drosophilidae) revised phylogenetically, with a new species group having peculiar lifecycles on monsteroid (Araceae) host plants. Systematic Entomology, 38, 763 - 782. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12027" type="journal article" year="2013">
Fartyal 
<emphasis box="[540,590,1188,1214]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
). Fore tarsomere II with 4 or 5 equal-sized pegs on lower elongation (ch.14-1,2; 
<figureCitation box="[282,397,1224,1250]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,903,927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,878]" captionTargetId="figure-22@12.[151,1435,181,879]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Characters 13‒15 on the fore (A, B, distal portion of tibia and tarsus) and mid (C, D, ditto) legs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, C) and C. cristata de Meijere (B, D). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766416/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 7A,B</figureCitation>
). Hypandrium posterolaterally connected to basal portion of phallal sheath through a pair of gonocoxites (
<figureCitation box="[302,383,1260,1286]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1315,1339]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-43@16.[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 11. Characters 40‒47 on the phallic organs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, ventral view; C, hypandrium and gonocoxites, oblique lateral view), C. xenalocasiae (Okada) (D, lateral view; E, ventral view), C. sabahana sp. nov. (F, lateral view; G, ventral view) and C. cristata de Meijere (H, lateral view; I, ventral view).Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; goncx, gonocoxite; hypd, hypandrium; phap, phallapodeme; ph sh, phallal sheath. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766424/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1187,1790]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,425,1295,1322]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Shared characters.</emphasis>
Arista entirely densely pubescent, without branches (
<figureCitation box="[1033,1152,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1541,1565]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1517]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1435,181,1517]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Characters 1‒4 on the head of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A‒D) and C. cristata de Meijere (E‒H). A, E, Caudal view; B, F, dorsal view; C, G, frontal view; D, H, right eye (frontal view). Abbreviations: ar, arista; a rc orb s, anterior reclinate orbital seta; i ocp s, inner occipital setae; pc orb s, proclinate orbital seta; spc s, supracervical setae. Character states are indicated in the form of ‘character No.-state code’. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766408/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 3C,G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1166,1217,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1350,1374]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,344,1326]" captionTargetId="figure-90@29.[151,1435,344,1326]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 19. Colocasiomyia cristata de Meijere (♂ and ♀ from Bogor, West Java, Indonesia). A, Antenna; B, dorsal portion of proboscis (caudal view; yellow arrowheads indicating supralateral setae outside prementum); C, male abdominal sternites (ventral view); D, female abdominal sternites (ventral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766444/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">19A</figureCitation>
). Anterior reclinate orbital seta situated outside proclinate orbital seta (
<figureCitation box="[728,840,1332,1358]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1541,1565]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1517]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1435,181,1517]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Characters 1‒4 on the head of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A‒D) and C. cristata de Meijere (E‒H). A, E, Caudal view; B, F, dorsal view; C, G, frontal view; D, H, right eye (frontal view). Abbreviations: ar, arista; a rc orb s, anterior reclinate orbital seta; i ocp s, inner occipital setae; pc orb s, proclinate orbital seta; spc s, supracervical setae. Character states are indicated in the form of ‘character No.-state code’. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766408" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766408/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 3B,F</figureCitation>
). Palpus more or less convex in ventrodistal portion, with prominent seta apically and several shorter ones medially to distally. All cibarial sensilla tiny; anterior sensilla irregularly arranged in square or triangle (
<figureCitation box="[644,717,1404,1430]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[151,250,798,822]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,773]" captionTargetId="figure-22@10.[151,1435,181,774]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. Characters 5 and 6 on the cibarium (dorsal view) of Colocasiomyia xenalocasiae (Okada) (A), C. cristata de Meijere (B) and C. sarawakana sp. nov. (C). Abbreviations: a s, anterior sensilla; m s, medial sensilla; p s, posterior sensillum; s c, sensilla campaniformia. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766410" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766410/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Proboscis without a pair of lateral spherical bumps covered with numerous, short, stout setae. Spiracles small. Abdominal sternite II wider than long, somewhat trapezoid or triangular, posteriorly narrowing. Epandrium anteroventrally much elongated, not fused to cercus, without peg-like, stout seta at posteroventral apex (
<figureCitation box="[537,692,1512,1538]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1695,1719]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,885,1666]" captionTargetId="figure-299@14.[151,1435,885,1672]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Characters 30‒39 on the periphallic organs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, anterior view), C. cristata de Meijere (C, lateral view; D, ventral view; E, surstylus) and C. xenalocasiae (Okada) (F, oblique lateral view; G, ventral view; H, surstylus). Abbreviations: cerc, cercus; epand, epandrium; sur, surstylus. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766422" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766422/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 10A,C,F</figureCitation>
). Pregonites absent (
<figureCitation box="[931,1015,1512,1538]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1315,1339]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-43@16.[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 11. Characters 40‒47 on the phallic organs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, ventral view; C, hypandrium and gonocoxites, oblique lateral view), C. xenalocasiae (Okada) (D, lateral view; E, ventral view), C. sabahana sp. nov. (F, lateral view; G, ventral view) and C. cristata de Meijere (H, lateral view; I, ventral view).Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; goncx, gonocoxite; hypd, hypandrium; phap, phallapodeme; ph sh, phallal sheath. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766424/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Hypandrium more or less quadrate plate-like, as wide as or slightly wider than phallapodeme, lacking setae, posteriorly articulated to tips of epandrial ventral elongations (
<figureCitation box="[378,458,1584,1610]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1315,1339]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-43@16.[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 11. Characters 40‒47 on the phallic organs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, ventral view; C, hypandrium and gonocoxites, oblique lateral view), C. xenalocasiae (Okada) (D, lateral view; E, ventral view), C. sabahana sp. nov. (F, lateral view; G, ventral view) and C. cristata de Meijere (H, lateral view; I, ventral view).Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; goncx, gonocoxite; hypd, hypandrium; phap, phallapodeme; ph sh, phallal sheath. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766424/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Phallapodeme horizontally flat, fused to phallal sheath (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1176,1584,1610]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1315,1339]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-43@16.[151,1435,237,1292]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 11. Characters 40‒47 on the phallic organs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, ventral view; C, hypandrium and gonocoxites, oblique lateral view), C. xenalocasiae (Okada) (D, lateral view; E, ventral view), C. sabahana sp. nov. (F, lateral view; G, ventral view) and C. cristata de Meijere (H, lateral view; I, ventral view).Abbreviations: aed, aedeagus; goncx, gonocoxite; hypd, hypandrium; phap, phallapodeme; ph sh, phallal sheath. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766424/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Oviscapt lateral lobes not fused to each other (
<figureCitation box="[422,516,1620,1647]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[242,1345,181,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-22@24.[242,1345,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 16. Colocasiomyia ecornuta Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Soppeng, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Head (frontal view); B, scutum and scutellum (dorsal view); C, D, abdominal sternites in ventral view (C, male; D, female); E, periphallic organs (caudolateral view; inset: cercal ventral lobe); F, phallal sheath (dorsal view); G, H, phallic organs (G, lateral view; H, ventral view); I peri-oviscapt (caudal view); J, oviscapt (ventral view); K, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion at lower right and ventrolateral portion of segments at the upper right); L, mouth hook; M, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Abbreviations: i vt s, inner vertical setae; sctl, scutellum. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–J and M, 1.0 mm in K." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766438/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 16J</figureCitation>
); ovisensilla all trichoid (
<figureCitation box="[801,931,1620,1646]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,762,786]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,182,734]" captionTargetId="figure-18@17.[151,1435,181,737]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Characters 48‒51 on the female terminalia of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (A, lateral view; B, hypoproct in ventral view) and C. cristata de Meijere (C, lateral view; D, hypoproct in ventral view). Abbreviations: epiprct, epiproct; hyprct, hypoproct; ov, oviscapt; t-VIII, tergite VIII. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766426/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 12A,C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
